<div id="post-1420" class="entry post-1420 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-particle-physics">

	<h2><a href="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/16/quark-contact-interactions-at-the-lhc/">Quark contact interactions at the&nbsp;LHC</a></h2>

	<p>So far, no convincing sign of new physics has been uncovered by the CMS and ATLAS collaborations.  Nonetheless, the scientists continue to look using a wide variety of approaches.  For example, a monumental work on the coupling of the Higgs boson to vector particles has been posted by the CMS Collaboration (<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1411.3441">arXiv:1411.3441</a>).   The authors conducted a thorough and very sophisticated statistical analysis of the kinematic distributions of all relevant decay modes, with the conclusion that the data for the Higgs boson are fully consistent with the standard model expectation.  The analysis and article are too long for a blog post, however, so please see the paper if you want to learn the details.</p>
<p>The ATLAS Collaboration posted a paper on generic searches for new physics signals based on events with three leptons (e, &mu; and &tau;). This paper (<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1411.2921">arXiv:1411.2921</a>) is longish one describing a broad-based search with several categories of events defined by lepton flavor and charge and other event properties.  In all categories the observation confirms the predictions based on standard model processes: the smallest p-value is 0.05.</p>
<p>A completely different search for new physics based on a decades-old concept was posted by CMS (<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1411.2646">arXiv:1411.2646</a>).  We all know that the Fermi theory of weak interactions starts with a so-called <i>contact interaction</i> characterized by an interaction vertex with four legs.  The Fermi constant serves to parametrize the interaction, and the participation of a vector boson is immaterial when the energy of the interaction is low compared to the boson mass. This framework is the starting point for other effective theories, and has been employed at hadron colliders when searching for deviations in quark-quark interactions, as might be observable if quarks were composite.</p>
<p>The experimental difficulty in studying high-energy quark-quark scattering is that the energies of the outgoing quarks are not so well measured as one might like. (First, the hadronic jets that materialize in the detector do not precisely reflect the quark energies, and second, jet energies cannot be measured better than a few percent.) It pays, therefore, to avoid using energy as an observable and to get the most out of angular variables, which are well measured.  Following analyses done at the Tevatron, the authors use a variable &chi; = exp(|y<sub>1</sub>-y<sub>2</sub>|), which is a simple function of the quark scattering angle in the center-of-mass frame.   The distribution of events in &chi; can be unambiguously predicted in the standard model and in any other hypothetical model, and confronted with the data.  So we have a nice case for a goodness-of-fit test and pairwise hypothesis testing.</p>
<p>The traditional parametrization of the interaction Lagrangian is:<br />
<a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/contact_lagrangian.png"><img data-attachment-id="1422" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/16/quark-contact-interactions-at-the-lhc/contact_lagrangian/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/contact_lagrangian.png" data-orig-size="758,65" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="contact_lagrangian" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/contact_lagrangian.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/contact_lagrangian.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/contact_lagrangian.png?w=455&#038;h=39" alt="contact_lagrangian"   class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1422" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/contact_lagrangian.png?w=455&amp;h=39 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/contact_lagrangian.png?w=150&amp;h=13 150w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/contact_lagrangian.png?w=300&amp;h=26 300w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/contact_lagrangian.png 758w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a><br />
where the &eta; parameters have values -1, 0, +1 and specify the chirality of the interaction; the key parameter is the mass scale &Lambda;.  An important detail is that this interaction Lagrangian can interfere with the standard model piece, and the interference can be either destructive or constructive, depending on the values of the &eta; parameters.</p>
<p>The analysis proceeds exactly as one would expect: events must have at least two jets, and when there are more than two, the two highest-pT jets are used and the others ignored.  Distributions of &chi; are formed for several ranges of di-jet invariant mass, M<sub>JJ</sub>, which extends as high as 5.2 TeV.  The measured &chi; distributions are unfolded, i.e., the effects of detector resolution are removed from the distribution on a statistical basis.  The main sources of systematic uncertainty come from the jet energy scale and resolution and are based on an extensive parametrization of jet uncertainties.</p>
<p>Since one is looking for deviations with respect to the standard model prediction, it is very important to have an accurate prediction.  Higher-order terms must be taken into account; these are available at next-to-leading order (NLO). In fact, even electroweak corrections are important and amount to several percent as a strong function of &chi; &#8212; see the plot on the right. <a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ewk_allmassbins_r05_authors.png"><img data-attachment-id="1423" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/16/quark-contact-interactions-at-the-lhc/ewk_allmassbins_r05_authors/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ewk_allmassbins_r05_authors.png" data-orig-size="255,255" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="EWK_AllMassBins_R05_authors" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ewk_allmassbins_r05_authors.png?w=255" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ewk_allmassbins_r05_authors.png?w=255" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ewk_allmassbins_r05_authors.png?w=455" alt="EWK_AllMassBins_R05_authors"   class="alignright size-full wp-image-1423" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ewk_allmassbins_r05_authors.png 255w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ewk_allmassbins_r05_authors.png?w=150 150w" sizes="(max-width: 255px) 100vw, 255px" /></a> The scale uncertainties are a few percent (again showing the a very precise SM prediction is non-trivial event for pp&rarr;2J) and fortunately the PDF uncertainties are small, at the percent level.  Theoretical uncertainties dominate for M<sub>JJ</sub> near 2 TeV, while statistical uncertainties dominate for M<sub>JJ</sub> above 4 TeV.</p>
<p>The money plot is this one:<br />
<a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/datacard_shapelimit_combined.png"><img data-attachment-id="1424" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/16/quark-contact-interactions-at-the-lhc/datacard_shapelimit_combined/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/datacard_shapelimit_combined.png" data-orig-size="842,595" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="datacard_shapelimit_combined" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Measured and predicted distributions in &amp;chi;&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/datacard_shapelimit_combined.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/datacard_shapelimit_combined.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/datacard_shapelimit_combined.png?w=455" alt="Measured and predicted distributions in &chi;" class="size-large wp-image-1424" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/datacard_shapelimit_combined.png?w=455 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/datacard_shapelimit_combined.png?w=150 150w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/datacard_shapelimit_combined.png?w=300 300w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/datacard_shapelimit_combined.png?w=768 768w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/datacard_shapelimit_combined.png 842w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a><br />
Optically speaking, the plot is not exciting: the &chi; distributions are basically flat and deviations due to a mass scale &Lambda; = 10 TeV would be mild.   Such deviations are not observed.   Notice, though, that the electroweak corrections do improve the agreement with the data in the lowest &chi; bins.  Loosely speaking, this improvement corresponds to about one standard deviation and therefore would be significant if CMS actually had evidence for new physics in these distributions.  As far as limits are concerned, the electroweak corrections are &#8220;worth&#8221; 0.5 TeV.</p>
<p>The statistical (in)significance of any deviation is quantified by a ratio of log-likelihoods: q = -2ln(L<sub>SM+NP</sub>/L<sub>SM</sub>) where SM stands for standard model and NP for new physics (i.e., one of distinct possibilities given in the interaction Lagrangian above).   Limits are derived on the mass scale &Lambda; depending on assumed values for the &eta; parameters; they are very nicely summarized in this graph:<a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ci_limits_summary.png"><img data-attachment-id="1425" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/16/quark-contact-interactions-at-the-lhc/ci_limits_summary/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ci_limits_summary.png" data-orig-size="842,595" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="CI_limits_summary" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Summary of limits placed on mass scales.&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ci_limits_summary.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ci_limits_summary.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ci_limits_summary.png?w=455" alt="Summary of limits placed on mass scales." class="size-large wp-image-1425" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ci_limits_summary.png?w=455 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ci_limits_summary.png?w=150 150w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ci_limits_summary.png?w=300 300w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ci_limits_summary.png?w=768 768w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/ci_limits_summary.png 842w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a><br />
The limits for contact interactions are roughly at the 10 TeV scale &#8212; well beyond the center-of-mass energy of 8 TeV.  I like this way of presenting the limits: you see the expected value (black dashed line) and an envelope of expected statistical fluctuations from this expectation, with the observed value clearly marked as a red line.   All limits are slightly more stringent than the expected ones (these are not independent of course).  </p>
<p>The authors also considered models of extra spatial dimensions and place limits on the scale of the extra dimensions at the 7 TeV level.</p>
<p>So, absolutely no sign of new physics here.  The LHC will turn on in 2015 at a significantly higher center-of-mass energy (13 TeV), and given the ability of this analysis to probe mass scales well above the proton-proton collision energy, a study of the &chi; distribution will be interesting.</p>

	<p class="info">	<em class="date"><a href="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/16/quark-contact-interactions-at-the-lhc/" title="10:45 am" rel="bookmark">November 16, 2014 at 10:45 am</a></em>				<em class="comments-popup">
		<a href="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/16/quark-contact-interactions-at-the-lhc/#comments" class="commentlink" >1 comment</a>		</em>
			</p>

</div>

	
<div id="post-1410" class="entry post-1410 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-particle-physics">

	<h2><a href="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/09/looking-for-milli-charged-particles-at-the-lhc/">Looking for milli-charged particles at the&nbsp;LHC</a></h2>

	<p>Andrew Haas, Chris Hill, Eder Izaguirre and Itay Yavin posted an interesting and imaginative proposal last week to search for milli-charged particles at ATLAS and CMS (<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1410.6816">arXiv:1410.6816</a>) and I think it is worth taking a look.</p>
<p>Milli-charged particles can arise in some models with extra gauge bosons.  The word &#8220;milli-charged&#8221; refers to the fact that the electric charge is much less than the charge of the electron.  Such small charges do not arise due to some fundamental representation in the gauge theory.  Rather, they arise through a (kinetic) mixing of the new gauge boson with the hyper charge field B<sub>&mu;</sub>.  If e&#8217; is the charge associated with the new gauge boson and &kappa; controls the degree of mixing, then the electric charge of the new particle &psi; is &epsilon; = &kappa;e&#8217; cos&theta;<sub>W</sub>/e.    The weak charge is smaller by a factor of tan&theta;<sub>W</sub>.   So the motivation for the search is good and the phenomenology is clear enough, and general.</p>
<p>A pair of hypothetical milli-charged particles would be produced through the Drell-Yan process.  There are contributions from both virtual photon and Z exchange; nonetheless, the cross section is small because the charge is small.   If the milli-charged particles are light enough, they can also be produced in decays of J/&psi; and &Upsilon; mesons.  The authors provide a plot:</p>
<div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_1412" style="width: 610px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/dy_prodxs_lhc.png"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-1412" data-attachment-id="1412" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/09/looking-for-milli-charged-particles-at-the-lhc/dy_prodxs_lhc/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/dy_prodxs_lhc.png" data-orig-size="600,394" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="DY_prodXS_LHC" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Cross section for the production of a pair of milli-charged particles&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/dy_prodxs_lhc.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/dy_prodxs_lhc.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/dy_prodxs_lhc.png?w=455" alt="Cross section for the production of a pair of milli-charged particles"   class="size-full wp-image-1412" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/dy_prodxs_lhc.png?w=455 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/dy_prodxs_lhc.png?w=150 150w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/dy_prodxs_lhc.png?w=300 300w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/dy_prodxs_lhc.png 600w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-1412" class="wp-caption-text">Cross section for the production of a pair of milli-charged particles</p></div>
<p>Detecting a milli-charged particle is not easy because the ionization they produce as they pass through matter is much smaller than that of an electron, muon or other standard charged particle.  (Recall that the ionization rate is proportional to the square of the charge of the particle.) Consequently, the trail of ions is much sparser and the amount of charge in a ionization cluster is smaller, resulting in a substantially or even dramatically reduced signal from a detector element (such as a silicon strip, proportional wire chamber or scintillator).  So they cannot be reliably reconstructed as tracks in an LHC or other general-purpose detector.  In fact, some searches have been done treating milli-charged particles as effectively invisible &#8211; i.e., as producing a missing energy signature.   Such approaches are not effective, however, due to the large background from Z&rarr;&nu;&nu;.</p>
<p>A special detector is required and this is the crux of the Haas, Hill, Izaguirre and Yavin proposal.</p>
<p>This special detector must have an unusually low threshold for ionization signals.  In fact, normal particles will produce relatively large signals that help reject them.  Clearly, the sensitivity to very small milli-charges, &epsilon;, is determined by how low the noise level in the detector is.  The main problem is that normal particles will swamp and bury any signal from milli-charged particles that may be present.  One needs to somehow shield the detector from normal particles so that one can look for small-amplitude signals from milli-charged particles.</p>
<p>Fortunately, the main challenge of detecting milli-charged particles turns out to be a virtue: normal particles will eventually be absorbed by bulk matter &#8211; this is the principle behind the calorimeter, after all.  Milli-charged particles, however, lose their energy through ionization at a much slower rate and will pass through the calorimeters with little attenuation.   This is the principle of the beam-dump experiment: look for particle that are <i>not</i> absorbed the way the known particles are.   (Implicitly we assume that the milli-charged particles have no strong interactions.)  </p>
<p>The authors propose to install a carefully-crafted scintillator detector behind a thick wall in the CMS and/or ATLAS caverns.  Typically, electronic readout devices for the normal detector are housed in a shielded room not far from the detector.  This new scintillator detector would be installed inside this so-called counting room.</p>
<div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_1414" style="width: 465px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/experimentschematicmillicharged.png"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-1414" data-attachment-id="1414" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/09/looking-for-milli-charged-particles-at-the-lhc/experimentschematicmillicharged/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/experimentschematicmillicharged.png" data-orig-size="1024,768" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="ExperimentSchematicMillicharged" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Schematics drawing showing how the scintillator detector would be placed in a counting room, away from the interaction point (IP)&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/experimentschematicmillicharged.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/experimentschematicmillicharged.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/experimentschematicmillicharged.png?w=455&#038;h=341" alt="Schematics drawing showing how the scintillator detector would be placed in a counting room, away from the interaction point (IP)"   class="size-large wp-image-1414" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/experimentschematicmillicharged.png?w=455&amp;h=341 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/experimentschematicmillicharged.png?w=910&amp;h=682 910w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/experimentschematicmillicharged.png?w=150&amp;h=113 150w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/experimentschematicmillicharged.png?w=300&amp;h=225 300w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/experimentschematicmillicharged.png?w=768&amp;h=576 768w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-1414" class="wp-caption-text">Schematics drawing showing how the scintillator detector would be placed in a counting room, away from the interaction point (IP)</p></div>
<p>The scintillator detector is not ordinary.  It must be sensitive to rather small ionization signals which means the amplification must be large and the noise rate low.  In order to fight spurious signals, the detector is divided into three parts along the flight path of the milli-charged particle and a coincidence of the three is required.  In order to fight backgrounds from ordinary particles produced in the pp collisions, the detector is segmented, with each segment subtending only a very small solid angle: essentially each segment (which consists of three longitudinal pieces) forms a telescope that points narrowly at the interaction point, i.e., the origin of the milli-charged particles.   Even with many such segments (&#8220;bars&#8221;), the total solid angle is miniscule so only a very small fraction of the signal would be detected &#8211; we say that the acceptance is very small.   Sensitivity to the production of milli-charged particles is possible because the luminosity of the LHC will be high.   Basically, the product of the cross section, the acceptance and the luminosity is a few even though the acceptance is so small.  The authors estimated the reach of their experiment and produced this figure:</p>
<p><a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/sensitivitythreelayersfigmillicharged.png"><img data-attachment-id="1417" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/09/looking-for-milli-charged-particles-at-the-lhc/sensitivitythreelayersfigmillicharged/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/sensitivitythreelayersfigmillicharged.png" data-orig-size="600,393" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="SensitivityThreeLayersFigMillicharged" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/sensitivitythreelayersfigmillicharged.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/sensitivitythreelayersfigmillicharged.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/sensitivitythreelayersfigmillicharged.png?w=455" alt="SensitivityThreeLayersFigMillicharged"   class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1417" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/sensitivitythreelayersfigmillicharged.png?w=455 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/sensitivitythreelayersfigmillicharged.png?w=150 150w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/sensitivitythreelayersfigmillicharged.png?w=300 300w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/11/sensitivitythreelayersfigmillicharged.png 600w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a></p>
<p>It is worth pointing out that this detector runs parasitically &#8211; it will not be providing triggers to the ATLAS or CMS detectors.   Its time resolution should be good, about 10 ns, so it might be possible to correlate a signal from a milli-charged particle with a particular bunch crossing, but this is not really needed.</p>
<p>The upcoming run will be an exciting time to try this search.   Evidence for milli-charged particles would be a huge discovery, of course.   I do not know the status of this proposal vis-a-vis CERN and the LHC experiments.  But if a signal were observed, it would clearly be easy to enhance it by building more detector.  My opinion is that this is a good idea, and I hope others will agree.</p>

	<p class="info">	<em class="date"><a href="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/09/looking-for-milli-charged-particles-at-the-lhc/" title="10:21 am" rel="bookmark">November 9, 2014 at 10:21 am</a></em>				<em class="comments-popup">
		<a href="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/11/09/looking-for-milli-charged-particles-at-the-lhc/#comments" class="commentlink" >1 comment</a>		</em>
			</p>

</div>

	
<div id="post-1397" class="entry post-1397 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-particle-physics">

	<h2><a href="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/10/26/the-cms-kinematic-edge/">The CMS kinematic&nbsp;edge</a></h2>

	<p>Does CMS observe an excess that corresponds to a signal for Supersymmetry?   Opinions differ.</p>
<p>This week a paper appeared with the statement &#8220;&#8230;CMS has reported an intriguing excess of events with respect to the ones expected in the SM&#8221; (Huang &amp; Wagner, <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1410.4998">arXiv:1410.4998</a>).  And last month another phenomenology paper   appeared with the title &#8220;Interpreting a CMS lljjpTmiss Excess With the Golden Cascade of the MSSM&#8221; (Allanach, Raklev and Kvellestad <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1409.3532">arXiv:1409.3532</a>).  Both studies are based on a preliminary CMS report (<a href="http://cds.cern.ch/record/1751493/files/SUS-12-019-pas.pdf">CMS PAS SUS-12-019</a>, Aug. 24 2014), which ends with the statement <i>&#8220;We do not observe evidence for a statistically significant signal.&#8221;</i>  </p>
<p>What is going on here?</p>
<p>The CMS search examines the di-lepton invariant mass distribution for a set of events which have, in addition to two energetic and isolated leptons, missing transverse momentum (pTmiss) and two jets.  In cascade decays of SUSY particles, &chi;02 &rarr; &chi;01 l+l-, a kind of hard edge appears at the phase space limit for the two leptons l+l-, as pointed out many years ago (PRD 55 (1997) 5520).   When distinguishing a signal from background, a sharp edge is almost as good as a peak, so this is a nice way to isolate a signal if one exists.   An edge can also be observed in decays of sleptons.  The CMS search is meant to be as general as possible.</p>
<p>In order to remove the bulk of SM events producing a pair of leptons, a significant missing energy is required, as expected from a pair of neutralinos &chi;01.  Furthermore, other activity in the event is expected (recall that there will be <i>two</i> supersymmetric particles in the event) so the search demands at least two jets.  Hence:  ll+jj+pTmiss.</p>
<p>A crucial feature of the analysis is motivated by the phenomenology of SUSY cascade decays: for the signal, the two leptons will have the same flavor (ee or &mu;&mu;), while most of the SM backgrounds will be flavor blind (so e&mu; also is expected).  By comparing the Mll spectrum for same-flavor and for opposite-flavor leptons, an excess might be observed with little reliance on simulations.  Only the Drell-Yan background does not appear in the opposite-flavor sample at the same level as in the same-flavor sample, but a hard cut on pTmiss (also called ETmiss) removes most of the DY background.  (I am glossing over careful and robust measurements of the relative e and &mu; reconstruction and trigger efficiencies &#8211; see the note for those details, especially Section 4.)</p>
<p>The CMS analyzers make an important distinction between &#8220;central&#8221; leptons with |&eta;|&lt;1.4 and &quot;forward&quot; leptons 1.6&lt;|&eta;|&lt;2.4 motivated by the idea that supersymmetric particles will be centrally produced due to their high mass, and an excess may be more pronounced when both leptons are central.</p>
<p>A search for a kinematic edge proceed just as you would expect &#8211; a series of fits is performed with the edge placed at different points across a wide range of invariant mass Mll.  The model for the Mll spectrum has three components: the flavor-symmetric backgrounds, dominated by tt, the DY background and a hypothetical signal.  Both the flavor-symmetric and the DY components are described by heuristic analytical functions with several free parameters.  The signal is a triangle convolved with a Gaussian to represent the resolution on Mll.  Most of the model parameters are determined in fits with enhanced DY contributions, and through the simultaneous fit to the opposite-flavor sample.  For the search, only three parameters are free: the signal yield in the central and forward regions and the position of the kinematic edge.</p>
<p>The best fitted value for the edge is y = 78.7&plusmn;1.4 GeV.  At that point, an excess is observed with a local statistical significance of 2.4&sigma;, in the central region.  There is no excess in the forward region. Here is the plot:</p>
<a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png"><img data-attachment-id="1400" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/10/26/the-cms-kinematic-edge/cms-edge/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png" data-orig-size="1181,1383" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="CMS edge" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Fit to the same-flavor dilepton mass distribution&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png?w=256" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png?w=455&#038;h=532" alt="Fit to the same-flavor dilepton mass distribution"   class="size-large wp-image-1400" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png?w=455&amp;h=532 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png?w=910&amp;h=1064 910w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png?w=128&amp;h=150 128w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png?w=256&amp;h=300 256w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png?w=768&amp;h=899 768w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge.png?w=874&amp;h=1024 874w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a>
<p>The green triangle represents the fitted signal.  The red peak is, of course, the Z resonance.  Here is the distribution for the forward region:</p>
<div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_1401" style="width: 465px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-1401" data-attachment-id="1401" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/10/26/the-cms-kinematic-edge/cms-edge-of/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png" data-orig-size="1181,1383" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="CMS edge OF" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Fit to the opposite (electron-muon) invariant mass distribution&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png?w=256" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png?w=455&#038;h=532" alt="Fit to the opposite invariant mass distribution for the forward sample"   class="size-large wp-image-1401" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png?w=455&amp;h=532 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png?w=910&amp;h=1064 910w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png?w=128&amp;h=150 128w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png?w=256&amp;h=300 256w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png?w=768&amp;h=899 768w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-of.png?w=874&amp;h=1024 874w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-1401" class="wp-caption-text">Fit to the opposite (electron-muon) invariant mass distribution</p></div>
<p>Comparing the two distributions and ignoring the Z peak, there does indeed seem to be an excess of ee and &mu;&mu; pairs for Mll &lt; 80 GeV or so.   One can understand why the theorists would find this intriguing&#8230;</p>
<p>CMS made a second treatment of their data by defining a mass region 20 &lt; Mll &lt; 70 GeV and simply counting the number of events, thereby avoiding any assumptions about the shape of a signal.  For this treatment, one wants to compare the data to the prediction, with suitable corrections for efficiencies, etc.  Here are the plots:</p>
<a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-mll-comparison.png"><img data-attachment-id="1402" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/10/26/the-cms-kinematic-edge/cms-mll-comparison/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-mll-comparison.png" data-orig-size="817,495" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="CMS Mll comparison" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Comparison of Mll distributions for data (dots) and the prediction (solid lines).  Left: central.  Right: forward.&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-mll-comparison.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-mll-comparison.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-mll-comparison.png?w=455&#038;h=275" alt="Comparison of Mll distributions for data (dots) and the prediction (solid lines).  Left: central.  Right: forward."   class="size-large wp-image-1402" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-mll-comparison.png?w=455&amp;h=275 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-mll-comparison.png?w=150&amp;h=91 150w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-mll-comparison.png?w=300&amp;h=182 300w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-mll-comparison.png?w=768&amp;h=465 768w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-mll-comparison.png 817w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a>
<p>By eye one can notice a tendency of the real data (dots) to fall above the prediction (solid line histogram).  This tendency is much stronger for the events with two central leptons compared to the events with at least one forward lepton.  Counting, CMS reports 860 observed compared to 730&plusmn;40 predicted (central) and 163 observed for 157&plusmn;16 forward.  The significance is 2.6&sigma; for the central di-leptons.</p>
<p>CMS provides a kind of teaser plot, in which they simulate three signals from the production of sbottom squarks.  As you can see here, two of the models describe the apparent excess well:</p>
<div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_1404" style="width: 608px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-sbottoms.png"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-1404" data-attachment-id="1404" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/10/26/the-cms-kinematic-edge/cms-edge-sbottoms/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-sbottoms.png" data-orig-size="598,549" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="CMS edge sbottoms" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Comparison to sbottom signals&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-sbottoms.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-sbottoms.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-sbottoms.png?w=455" alt="Comparison to sbottom signals"   class="size-full wp-image-1404" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-sbottoms.png?w=455 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-sbottoms.png?w=150 150w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-sbottoms.png?w=300 300w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/cms-edge-sbottoms.png 598w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-1404" class="wp-caption-text">Comparison to sbottom signals</p></div>
<p>So why is this not a discovery?</p>
<p>First of all, the statistical significance is under 3&sigma; so formally speaking, this not even &#8220;evidence.&#8221;  More importantly, the &#8220;look-elsewhere effect&#8221; has not been taken into account, as stated clearly in the CMS note.  In other words, the significance for the fit is 2.4&sigma; <i>when you choose 78.7 GeV for the position of the edge.</i>   If you allow for any position of the edge within some wide range of Mll, then the chance that you observe an excess <i>somewhere in that range</i> is much greater than 1%.  Similarly, the counting excess is 2.6&sigma; for the specific box 20 &lt; Mll &lt; 70 GeV, but if you consider many different boxes, the chance to observe such a single excess <i>somewhere</i> is not so small.   For this reason, the CMS Collaboration states that there is no statistically significant excess.</p>
<p>That said, the agreement of the simulated sbottom signals with the data is striking, even granted that there are many free parameters here that one can tune to get a good description.  The Allanach et al. paper reports a scan in MSSM parameter space to find which physical SUSY parameters are consistent with the CMS data.  They impose a few theoretical constraints that are not crucial at this stage, and perform a scan with simulated signals to see which ranges of parameters reproduce the CMS data and also respect constraints from other ATLAS and CMS searches.  An example model is shown here: </p>
<div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_1406" style="width: 465px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/200_300-eps-converted-to.png"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-1406" data-attachment-id="1406" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/10/26/the-cms-kinematic-edge/200_300-eps-converted-to/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/200_300-eps-converted-to.png" data-orig-size="866,558" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="200_300-eps-converted-to" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Example spectrum from Allanach et al.&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/200_300-eps-converted-to.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/200_300-eps-converted-to.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/200_300-eps-converted-to.png?w=455&#038;h=293" alt="Example spectrum from Allanach et al."   class="size-large wp-image-1406" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/200_300-eps-converted-to.png?w=455&amp;h=293 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/200_300-eps-converted-to.png?w=150&amp;h=97 150w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/200_300-eps-converted-to.png?w=300&amp;h=193 300w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/200_300-eps-converted-to.png?w=768&amp;h=495 768w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/200_300-eps-converted-to.png 866w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-1406" class="wp-caption-text">Example spectrum from Allanach et al.</p></div>
<p>Wide ranges of sparticle masses are allowed, but there are strong constraints among them coming from the well-measured position of the edge.  Constraints from (g-1)&mu; are respected and the relic density is good.  Best of all, prospects for discovering one of these models at Run 2 are good &#8212; if such a signal really is present of course.</p>
<p>The Huang &amp; Wagner paper focuses on the sbottom scenario mentioned in the CMS paper, and does a more detailed and refined analysis.  They define two similar scenarios, here is the scheme for the first one:</p>
<div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_1407" style="width: 633px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/sbottom-scenario.png"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-1407" data-attachment-id="1407" data-permalink="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/10/26/the-cms-kinematic-edge/sbottom-scenario/" data-orig-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/sbottom-scenario.png" data-orig-size="623,454" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="sbottom scenario" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Huang &amp;amp; Wagner sbottom scenario&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/sbottom-scenario.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/sbottom-scenario.png?w=455" src="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/sbottom-scenario.png?w=455" alt="Huang &amp; Wagner sbottom scenario"   class="size-full wp-image-1407" srcset="https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/sbottom-scenario.png?w=455 455w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/sbottom-scenario.png?w=150 150w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/sbottom-scenario.png?w=300 300w, https://muon.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/sbottom-scenario.png 623w" sizes="(max-width: 455px) 100vw, 455px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-1407" class="wp-caption-text">Huang &amp; Wagner sbottom scenario</p></div>
<p>They do not perform a scan of parameter space; rather, they select model parameters by hand to provide pertinent examples.  They specifically focus on the relic density and (g-2)&mu; to make sure they their model can explain these facts.  They explain their reasoning clearly in their paper.  Their hand-tuned model does a nice job matching the CMS data.  Of course, it also evades direct searches for sbottoms by both ATLAS and CMS.  </p>
<p>What about the ATLAS 8 TeV data?  For now, we must wait.</p>

	<p class="info">	<em class="date"><a href="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/10/26/the-cms-kinematic-edge/" title="5:29 pm" rel="bookmark">October 26, 2014 at 5:29 pm</a></em>				<em class="comments-popup">
		<a href="https://muon.wordpress.com/2014/10/26/the-cms-kinematic-edge/#comments" class="commentlink" >2 comments</a>		</em>
